WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:09.700
Oxford Bookworms, Stage 1. Pocahontas, retold by Tim Vickery, read

00:09.700 --> 00:11.280
by Oliver Winen.

00:11.280 --> 00:16.500
Copyright Oxford University Press 2005.

00:34.360 --> 00:39.660
Chapter 1. The English in Virginia.

00:41.180 --> 00:50.480
In January 1607, three ships left England and sailed to

00:50.480 --> 00:57.560
America. There were 150 men on the ships and they

00:57.560 --> 01:02.900
wanted to find a new world in the West, a

01:02.900 --> 01:06.660
home in a new and exciting country.

01:07.660 --> 01:13.240
The ships were at sea for four months and they

01:13.240 --> 01:20.860
arrived in Virginia on the 26th April 1607.

01:21.860 --> 01:27.600
After four long months at sea, the men were tired,

01:28.400 --> 01:37.260
ill and hungry. But Virginia was beautiful. The sky was

01:37.260 --> 01:43.560
blue and they could see rivers and flowers and forests

01:43.560 --> 01:45.400
of tall trees.

01:45.400 --> 01:54.240
The Englishmen were very happy. But the Algonquin Indians of

01:54.240 --> 02:00.940
Virginia were not happy. They were afraid of the Englishmen

02:00.940 --> 02:02.500
and their ships.

02:03.820 --> 02:11.000
This is our home, they said. We don't want these

02:11.000 --> 02:15.360
white men here. We must fight them.

02:16.460 --> 02:24.720
But some Indians said, no, wait. These men are interesting.

02:26.200 --> 02:30.320
Let's make friends with them and learn about them.

02:31.440 --> 02:37.200
So the Indians tried to talk to the Englishmen and

02:37.200 --> 02:42.800
gave them food to eat. The Englishmen gave things to

02:42.800 --> 02:48.820
the Indians too, little knives and pictures and beads.

02:50.400 --> 02:57.020
The Englishmen began to build a little town. They called

02:57.020 --> 03:02.540
it Jamestown because the king of England was called James.

03:03.420 --> 03:07.480
They called the River James River too.

03:08.480 --> 03:15.700
The leaders of the Englishmen were Christopher Newport, Edward Wingfield

03:15.700 --> 03:22.280
and John Smith. They wanted to learn more about Virginia,

03:23.400 --> 03:28.920
so Smith and Newport took twenty men and went up

03:28.920 --> 03:31.340
the river in a small boat.

03:32.340 --> 03:39.100
The other men stayed in Jamestown with Wingfield. They began

03:39.100 --> 03:44.800
to build houses and to make gardens and fields outside

03:44.800 --> 03:45.920
the town.

03:47.240 --> 03:53.700
The fields are more important than the houses, said Wingfield.

03:54.540 --> 04:00.300
And we must work quickly because it's nearly summer now.

04:00.820 --> 04:07.280
We must have corn and vegetables for the winter. But

04:07.280 --> 04:13.160
it was not easy. The weather was hot. And the

04:13.160 --> 04:15.900
men were tired after four months.

04:15.920 --> 04:22.400
At sea, some men worked hard, but many sat in

04:22.400 --> 04:29.180
the sun and did nothing. The Indians watched and waited.

04:30.220 --> 04:36.460
Smith and Newport went a hundred kilometers up the river.

04:37.220 --> 04:42.620
They visited Indian villages and talked to a lot of

04:42.620 --> 04:43.100
Indians.

04:44.100 --> 04:50.180
Some of the Indians were friendly, and some were not.

04:51.240 --> 04:58.320
When Smith and Newport came back to Jamestown, Wingfield was

04:58.320 --> 05:00.520
very pleased to see them.

05:01.100 --> 05:08.060
I was afraid for you, he said, but you're not

05:08.060 --> 05:08.520
dead.

05:09.580 --> 05:15.720
No, of course not, said Smith. What's the matter?

05:16.720 --> 05:23.240
It's the Indians, Wingfield said. They're trying to kill us.

05:23.880 --> 05:27.440
Yesterday they nearly killed me.

05:28.400 --> 05:34.800
Well, what did you do? Smith asked. Our men have

05:34.800 --> 05:39.260
guns, and the Indians are very afraid of guns.

05:40.500 --> 05:48.420
But there were hundreds of Indians, said Wingfield, and we

05:48.420 --> 05:52.560
weren't ready. Our guns were on the ships.

05:55.180 --> 06:02.600
Why, asked Smith angrily, the men must always be ready.

06:03.300 --> 06:06.280
They must carry their guns with them.

06:07.200 --> 06:12.000
The Indians tried to kill you because they weren't afraid

06:12.000 --> 06:12.720
of you.

06:14.180 --> 06:20.700
Yes, but we must be nice to them, said Wingfield.

06:21.880 --> 06:28.160
We can be friendly, but we must be careful first,

06:28.900 --> 06:29.900
said Smith.

06:30.500 --> 06:35.480
We must build good walls round the town and put

06:35.480 --> 06:38.260
the big guns from the ships on them.

06:38.890 --> 06:45.280
Then the Indians can't kill us. For a month everyone

06:45.280 --> 06:49.940
worked hard. They built walls round the town

06:49.940 --> 06:55.600
and moved the big guns from the ships. But the

06:55.600 --> 07:00.140
men were afraid to work in the fields because of

07:00.140 --> 07:00.760
the Indians,

07:01.740 --> 07:08.980
and the sun got hotter and hotter. In June Newport

07:08.980 --> 07:12.780
went back to England with two of the ships.

07:14.300 --> 07:20.160
A hundred and five men stayed in Jamestown. They had

07:20.160 --> 07:21.960
very little food.

07:22.960 --> 07:28.280
The corn from England was now bad, and the new

07:28.280 --> 07:31.200
corn in the fields was not ready.

07:32.380 --> 07:37.880
The river water was bad too, and soon many of

07:37.880 --> 07:40.080
the men were ill with a fever.

07:41.080 --> 07:44.560
Forty-six men died that summer.

07:46.040 --> 07:51.320
Some of the men tried to leave Jamestown and go

07:51.320 --> 07:55.820
home in the ship, but Smith stopped them.

07:57.020 --> 08:01.880
We're here to work and to build a new town,

08:02.420 --> 08:07.560
he said. But first we must find food.

08:08.620 --> 08:13.160
There are birds in the sky, fish in the river,

08:14.180 --> 08:19.260
animals in the forest. We must kill them and eat

08:19.260 --> 08:19.700
them.

08:19.700 --> 08:25.900
And we must get corn from the Indians too. I

08:25.900 --> 08:26.860
can do that.

08:28.240 --> 08:33.660
Smith wasn't afraid of the Indians, but he was always

08:33.660 --> 08:39.480
very careful. He carried his gun all the time.

08:40.480 --> 08:45.680
Most of the Indians were afraid of Smith, but they

08:45.680 --> 08:46.900
liked him too.

08:47.680 --> 08:54.360
He was friendly, and he loved their beautiful country. And

08:54.360 --> 08:57.220
he learned their language because

08:57.220 --> 09:01.640
he wanted to talk to them and understand them.

09:02.640 --> 09:08.500
Often he gave the Indians little things from England, and

09:08.500 --> 09:10.280
they gave him food.

09:11.860 --> 09:18.360
But when winter came, there were only fifty men alive

09:18.360 --> 09:25.320
in Jamestown. They had some food, but they needed more.

09:26.280 --> 09:32.620
The Virginian winter is long and cold, and fifty men

09:32.620 --> 09:34.940
need a lot of food.

09:36.500 --> 09:41.140
In December, Smith went up the river in a boat

09:41.140 --> 09:46.880
with nine men. Two of the friendly Indians went with

09:46.880 --> 09:47.200
them.

09:47.200 --> 09:54.500
It was very cold, and the Englishmen were hungry. But

09:54.500 --> 09:57.640
Smith was happy and excited.

09:59.900 --> 10:05.340
I'm going to find food for Christmas, he said to

10:05.340 --> 10:06.960
the man in Jamestown.

10:06.960 --> 10:13.280
Wait for me here, and work hard. This is a

10:13.280 --> 10:17.880
beautiful country, and we're going to stay here.

10:36.960 --> 10:42.700
Chapter 2 John Smith and Pocahontas

10:45.310 --> 10:51.140
There were a lot of Indian villages in Virginia, and

10:51.140 --> 10:57.980
every village had its chief. But there was only one

10:57.980 --> 10:58.760
king.

10:59.760 --> 11:05.560
That was Powhatan, and he was the king of all

11:05.560 --> 11:07.300
the Algonquin Indians.

11:08.960 --> 11:14.840
Tell me about these white men. Powhatan said to his

11:14.840 --> 11:17.280
brother, Opecan Canu.

11:18.520 --> 11:24.520
They are living in my country, and killing my people.

11:25.600 --> 11:27.920
I want to see one of them.

11:30.420 --> 11:38.540
Powhatan's daughter, Pocahontas, heard this. She was thirteen years old.

11:39.660 --> 11:46.140
What are white men, father? She asked. Are they white

11:46.140 --> 11:47.800
because they are ill?

11:49.720 --> 11:51.100
Powhatan smiled.

11:52.100 --> 11:57.980
No, little Pocahontas. They aren't ill, he said.

11:58.660 --> 12:04.460
They are a new people from over the sea. Perhaps

12:04.460 --> 12:08.280
we can see and talk to a white man soon.

12:09.240 --> 12:12.840
My brother is going to find one for us.

12:15.060 --> 12:21.360
The next day, Opecan Canu went into the forest with

12:21.360 --> 12:28.360
two hundred men. They found John Smith's nine men next

12:28.360 --> 12:30.680
to their boat by the river.

12:31.920 --> 12:38.440
Smith's men were afraid and got out their guns. But

12:38.440 --> 12:42.420
Opecan Canu's men killed two of them,

12:43.320 --> 12:45.980
and the other seven ran away.

12:47.540 --> 12:52.180
John Smith was in the forest with the two Indians.

12:53.160 --> 12:57.980
When they heard the noise, they ran back to the

12:57.980 --> 13:03.880
boat and saw two hundred men with bows and arrows.

13:05.200 --> 13:12.200
Then an arrow hit Smith's leg. He quickly took out

13:12.200 --> 13:17.200
his gun and put a friendly Indian in front of

13:17.200 --> 13:17.860
his body.

13:19.640 --> 13:25.540
What do you want? He asked. Don't come near me.

13:27.540 --> 13:34.260
King Powhatan wants to see you, said Opecan Canu. Give

13:34.260 --> 13:35.260
me your gun.

13:36.660 --> 13:43.980
No, Smith said at first, but there were two hundred

13:43.980 --> 13:47.680
Indians, and he was one man.

13:48.660 --> 13:55.000
So he gave them his gun and went with Opecan

13:55.000 --> 14:01.340
Canu to Werowakomoko, the village of King Powhatan.

14:02.780 --> 14:09.120
In the village, everyone came out to see the Englishman.

14:10.660 --> 14:19.460
Pocahontas looked at Smith carefully. He was very interesting. He

14:19.460 --> 14:24.600
was not very tall, and he had hair on his

14:24.600 --> 14:25.080
face.

14:26.080 --> 14:32.180
Indian men had no hair on their faces, and his

14:32.180 --> 14:35.660
eyes. His eyes were blue.

14:36.780 --> 14:42.680
All the men in her village had brown eyes. She

14:42.680 --> 14:47.200
looked at Smith's blue eyes for a long time.

14:47.200 --> 14:52.360
They were beautiful, the color of the sky.

14:54.820 --> 15:00.440
Smith smiled at the little girl and closed one of

15:00.440 --> 15:02.100
his eyes for a second.

15:03.920 --> 15:09.080
Pocahontas laughed, and then she smiled back at him.

15:11.640 --> 15:18.440
Why are you in my country, white man? Powhatan asked.

15:19.920 --> 15:24.340
Where do you come from? Who is your king?

15:26.280 --> 15:33.100
Smith told him about England and King James and Jamestown.

15:33.760 --> 15:41.860
It wasn't easy, because he didn't understand Powhatan's language very

15:41.860 --> 15:48.120
well, and Powhatan didn't always understand him.

15:49.120 --> 15:55.100
We want to live here, and be your friends, Powhatan,

15:55.520 --> 15:56.260
he said.

15:57.260 --> 16:03.420
But this winter, the people of Jamestown are hungry, so

16:03.420 --> 16:05.280
we need food.

16:07.580 --> 16:10.240
Opecan Canu was angry.

16:11.400 --> 16:16.860
These Englishmen cannot live here, he said to his brother.

16:18.040 --> 16:22.840
They are taking our land, and killing our people with

16:22.840 --> 16:23.560
their guns.

16:24.380 --> 16:29.080
They want King James of England to be king here

16:29.080 --> 16:29.600
too.

16:30.580 --> 16:36.220
They call their town King James's town, and they call

16:36.220 --> 16:39.860
our beautiful river King James's river.

16:40.580 --> 16:45.520
But what about us? This is our country.

16:46.380 --> 16:52.340
We live here, and our fathers and grandfathers lived here

16:52.340 --> 16:53.340
before us.

16:53.340 --> 16:58.640
We don't want the English or their King James.

16:59.440 --> 17:02.800
We must kill them all now.

17:05.780 --> 17:10.580
Perhaps, Powhatan said, but let's think first.

17:11.760 --> 17:17.340
The English have guns, so we need guns too.

17:18.340 --> 17:21.360
I must think carefully about this.

17:22.580 --> 17:25.120
Pocahontas, come with me.

17:27.120 --> 17:33.300
They walked into the forest, and Powhatan asked his daughter.

17:34.460 --> 17:39.840
What do you think about this Englishman, little Pocahontas?

17:40.860 --> 17:47.680
Oh, father, I like him. He has wonderful blue eyes,

17:48.500 --> 17:50.060
the color of the sky.

17:51.960 --> 17:56.580
My brother wants to kill him, but I want to

17:56.580 --> 18:01.720
know more about these Englishmen first, and you can help

18:01.720 --> 18:02.060
me.

18:03.060 --> 18:07.300
I'm going to give him to you, little Pocahontas.

18:08.320 --> 18:10.640
Give him to me, father.

18:11.680 --> 18:17.920
Yes, listen carefully now. You must do this.

18:20.240 --> 18:22.980
They went back to the village.

18:24.540 --> 18:29.840
Are we going to kill this white man now, Powhatan?

18:30.600 --> 18:32.360
Opecan Canu asked.

18:33.280 --> 18:38.260
Yes, Powhatan said. Bring him here.

18:39.900 --> 18:45.360
They put John Smith's head on a stone, in front

18:45.360 --> 18:47.120
of Powhatan's feet.

18:48.120 --> 18:54.620
Then, Opecan Canu took a big stick and walked to

18:54.620 --> 18:55.160
the stone.

18:56.820 --> 19:01.980
Pocahontas looked at her father. He moved his head a

19:01.980 --> 19:04.800
little, but did not look at her.

19:06.500 --> 19:10.900
Now, Opecan Canu was next to the stone.

19:11.900 --> 19:17.340
John Smith closed his eyes and waited to die.

19:19.540 --> 19:25.520
Suddenly, he felt warm arms on his face and head.

19:26.560 --> 19:30.980
He opened his eyes and saw the face of the

19:30.980 --> 19:35.280
young girl with her beautiful dark eyes.

19:36.920 --> 19:40.580
No, Opecan Canu. She cried.

19:42.140 --> 19:47.500
No, I am the king's daughter, and I say no.

19:48.620 --> 19:50.880
She looked at her father.

19:52.060 --> 19:59.020
Father, don't kill this man. Please, give him to me.

20:00.480 --> 20:08.880
At first, Powhatan said nothing. Then, slowly, he smiled.

20:10.540 --> 20:13.860
Very well, Pocahontas, he said.

20:14.820 --> 20:19.960
You are only thirteen years old, but this white man

20:19.960 --> 20:21.580
is not very big.

20:22.200 --> 20:26.360
He is a boy with hair on his face. You

20:26.360 --> 20:27.340
can have him.

20:29.000 --> 20:33.960
Angrily, Opecan Canu put his stick down.

20:35.860 --> 20:37.460
Pocahontas smiled.

20:38.880 --> 20:42.800
Come with me, white man, she said to him.

20:43.860 --> 20:47.380
You are my English man now. Come.

21:05.920 --> 21:10.860
Chapter 3 A Friend for the English

21:13.340 --> 21:18.740
John Smith stayed with Pocahontas for some days.

21:19.520 --> 21:24.840
She learned some English, and he learned more of her

21:24.840 --> 21:25.480
language.

21:26.480 --> 21:29.840
Soon, they were good friends.

21:31.520 --> 21:38.340
But Powhatan's men watched Smith carefully, and he could not

21:38.340 --> 21:39.680
leave the village.

21:40.860 --> 21:44.880
Then, one day, Powhatan said,

21:45.960 --> 21:50.080
You can go home to Jamestown John Smith,

21:50.080 --> 21:55.580
but you must give me two of your big guns.

21:57.720 --> 22:03.520
John Smith did not like this, but he could not

22:03.520 --> 22:04.480
say no.

22:05.720 --> 22:12.920
So he went back to Jamestown, and Pocahontas, Opecan Canu,

22:13.600 --> 22:16.100
and some Indians went with him.

22:19.280 --> 22:24.040
In Jamestown, Wingfield was not happy.

22:25.060 --> 22:30.020
We can't give our big guns to the Indians, he

22:30.020 --> 22:30.420
said.

22:31.360 --> 22:34.920
Then they can kill us with our guns.

22:36.080 --> 22:38.980
It's all right, said Smith.

22:40.300 --> 22:40.420
Wait.

22:41.420 --> 22:46.880
He took Opecan Canu and his men to the guns

22:46.880 --> 22:48.540
on the town walls.

22:49.880 --> 22:52.620
Now watch, he said.

22:53.540 --> 22:58.360
He put some gunpowder and some stones in the gun.

22:59.800 --> 23:04.280
Put your hands over your ears, he said,

23:05.220 --> 23:07.160
and look at that tree.

23:08.640 --> 23:09.720
Bang!

23:11.100 --> 23:13.720
Pocahontas closed her eyes.

23:14.660 --> 23:19.000
Then she opened them and looked at the tree.

23:19.920 --> 23:21.680
It wasn't there.

23:22.840 --> 23:24.360
What happened?

23:25.420 --> 23:25.960
She asked.

23:26.940 --> 23:28.040
Where's the tree?

23:29.920 --> 23:34.260
I killed it with this gun, Smith said.

23:35.260 --> 23:38.300
He looked at Opecan Canu.

23:38.900 --> 23:44.500
This gun can kill ten men, Opecan Canu.

23:45.080 --> 23:46.580
Remember that.

23:47.500 --> 23:50.200
So, take your two guns.

23:52.140 --> 23:58.160
But the guns were very big, and of course, the

23:58.160 --> 24:00.680
Indians could not move them.

24:03.820 --> 24:06.500
Look, said Smith.

24:07.420 --> 24:11.180
You can't carry these guns through the forest.

24:12.220 --> 24:16.720
But I can give you some gunpowder for Powhatan.

24:17.420 --> 24:19.480
Here, take it.

24:20.260 --> 24:22.640
Be very careful with it.

24:24.060 --> 24:28.140
Thank you, Opecan Canu said.

24:29.080 --> 24:33.320
But one day we want these big guns too.

24:34.220 --> 24:36.900
They are very important for us.

24:37.780 --> 24:40.460
Perhaps, said Smith,

24:41.200 --> 24:44.020
but we want to be your friends.

24:44.820 --> 24:48.060
And friends are better than guns.

24:51.300 --> 24:59.280
That winter, Pocahontas came to Jamestown every week with food

24:59.280 --> 25:00.940
for the Englishmen.

25:01.880 --> 25:06.540
She learned many interesting things in Jamestown.

25:08.960 --> 25:11.600
Look at this, Pocahontas.

25:12.500 --> 25:14.740
John Smith said one day.

25:14.740 --> 25:18.100
He had a compass in his hand.

25:19.220 --> 25:20.760
What is it?

25:21.580 --> 25:22.920
Pocahontas asked.

25:23.960 --> 25:27.920
She tried to put her finger on the arrow in

25:27.920 --> 25:30.540
the compass, but she couldn't.

25:31.440 --> 25:32.440
It's a compass.

25:33.480 --> 25:37.160
The arrow always points to the north.

25:38.140 --> 25:39.120
Smith said.

25:40.460 --> 25:42.140
Where is the north?

25:42.140 --> 25:43.900
Do you know?

25:44.760 --> 25:46.760
Of course I know.

25:47.600 --> 25:49.760
All my people know that.

25:50.920 --> 25:52.880
Well, look.

25:53.660 --> 25:57.160
The arrow in the compass knows it too.

25:59.300 --> 26:02.680
Why can't I put my finger on it?

26:03.720 --> 26:05.300
Smith smiled.

26:06.400 --> 26:07.760
Because of the glass.

26:08.760 --> 26:13.120
You can see through glass, but you can't put your

26:13.120 --> 26:14.320
finger through it.

26:15.980 --> 26:24.140
Yes, she said slowly, but what is a compass for?

26:25.760 --> 26:29.820
It helps us in our ships when we can't see

26:29.820 --> 26:31.860
the sky, he said.

26:32.820 --> 26:34.680
Which way do we go?

26:35.420 --> 26:36.820
Where is the north?

26:38.000 --> 26:40.680
The compass tells us all that.

26:42.640 --> 26:46.380
Pocahontas was interested in everything.

26:47.540 --> 26:52.480
She loved to talk to John Smith, and she learned

26:52.480 --> 26:57.040
many things about England and the English.

26:58.460 --> 27:07.140
In March and April 1608, two more ships came to

27:07.140 --> 27:08.040
Jamestown.

27:09.160 --> 27:12.840
Paul Hatton asked Pocahontas about them.

27:13.920 --> 27:18.360
How many Englishmen are there now?

27:19.000 --> 27:19.640
He asked.

27:20.640 --> 27:25.620
There were thirty-eight before the ships came, Father.

27:26.260 --> 27:30.700
But now there are about a hundred and fifty.

27:32.100 --> 27:33.940
It's spring now.

27:34.680 --> 27:38.540
They must sow corn and vegetables in their fields.

27:39.320 --> 27:40.740
Are they doing that?

27:41.700 --> 27:46.780
Yes, Father, but they aren't very good at it.

27:46.780 --> 27:50.360
This is a new country for them.

27:50.880 --> 27:53.360
They don't understand it.

27:55.300 --> 27:58.100
But they must have corn.

27:59.260 --> 28:01.260
Paul Hatton was angry.

28:02.080 --> 28:04.960
They need food for the winter.

28:05.800 --> 28:11.360
We can't give them our corn every year, and we

28:11.360 --> 28:16.160
kill animals, birds, and fish for our food.

28:16.780 --> 28:20.120
The English must learn to do that too.

28:21.560 --> 28:26.320
They are learning, Father, Pocahontas said.

28:27.060 --> 28:32.260
But most of these men come from towns in England.

28:33.060 --> 28:35.660
They don't know about these things.

28:37.140 --> 28:43.240
Well, they live here now, so they must learn, said

28:43.240 --> 28:44.060
Paul Hatton.

28:44.060 --> 28:47.780
Or they must give me guns.

28:48.880 --> 28:53.080
We have a lot of food in our village, but

28:53.080 --> 28:54.440
we need guns.

28:55.300 --> 28:58.300
I can give the Englishmen food.

28:59.360 --> 29:02.720
But they must give me guns first.

29:03.700 --> 29:07.620
Tell that to your English friends, Pocahontas.

29:26.160 --> 29:31.500
Chapter 4 A Wife for John Smith

29:33.560 --> 29:38.700
But the English didn't want to give Paul Hatton any

29:38.700 --> 29:39.240
guns.

29:40.680 --> 29:43.400
Oh no, Pocahontas.

29:43.920 --> 29:45.260
John Smith said.

29:46.080 --> 29:50.960
Your father has thousands of men, but we have only

29:50.960 --> 29:51.620
150.

29:52.960 --> 29:55.440
We can't give him guns.

29:56.720 --> 30:02.100
Later, some of Paul Hatton's men tried to take guns

30:02.100 --> 30:03.260
from the English.

30:04.160 --> 30:07.000
Smith was very angry.

30:07.870 --> 30:12.800
He locked the men in a little room in Jamestown

30:12.800 --> 30:14.060
for a week.

30:14.900 --> 30:18.600
Then he talked to Pocahontas about them.

30:21.060 --> 30:27.020
I'm very angry with these men, Pocahontas, he said.

30:27.580 --> 30:32.820
But I'm not going to kill them, because your father

30:32.820 --> 30:34.560
didn't kill me

30:34.560 --> 30:36.720
in where I will comical.

30:37.520 --> 30:40.780
I'm going to give them to you.

30:41.660 --> 30:44.080
Take them home, Pocahontas.

30:46.640 --> 30:52.580
Pocahontas liked the English, and she often visited Jamestown.

30:53.500 --> 30:57.300
John Smith liked to teach her new things.

30:59.380 --> 31:05.580
The sun, Pocahontas, he said one evening, is a red

31:05.580 --> 31:07.360
ball in the sky.

31:08.460 --> 31:11.940
This world is a big round ball, too.

31:13.060 --> 31:19.160
Thirty years ago, an English man called Francis Drake sailed

31:19.160 --> 31:21.660
round the world in a ship.

31:24.420 --> 31:28.580
Pocahontas laughed, but that's not true.

31:29.420 --> 31:32.080
Of course the world isn't a ball.

31:32.920 --> 31:35.600
Why does the sea stay on it, then?

31:36.780 --> 31:38.280
Smith smiled.

31:39.700 --> 31:42.980
Oh, I can tell you, listen.

31:44.340 --> 31:49.540
He talked well, so it was easy to understand him.

31:51.400 --> 31:56.940
Pocahontas listened and watched his beautiful blue eyes.

31:58.000 --> 32:04.740
She was fourteen years old, and for her, John Smith

32:04.740 --> 32:08.600
was the most exciting man in the world.

32:10.220 --> 32:13.840
Do you have a wife, John Smith?

32:14.560 --> 32:16.200
She asked one day.

32:17.160 --> 32:20.360
No, he said slowly.

32:21.420 --> 32:23.020
Why do you ask?

32:24.080 --> 32:30.660
Oh, because one day I must have a husband, and

32:30.660 --> 32:36.220
she did not finish, but John Smith understood.

32:38.800 --> 32:46.620
Pocahontas, he said carefully, you are only fourteen years old,

32:47.200 --> 32:49.180
and I'm twenty-eight,

32:49.740 --> 32:55.340
and the daughter of the king must marry somebody important.

32:56.980 --> 33:02.900
You are an important man in Jamestown, she said quickly.

33:02.900 --> 33:08.480
And my people and your people must learn to be

33:08.480 --> 33:09.040
friends.

33:09.700 --> 33:13.800
A husband and wife can stop.

33:15.020 --> 33:17.780
He put his finger on her mouth.

33:19.500 --> 33:25.240
Pocahontas, I like you very much, but I'm not the

33:25.240 --> 33:31.080
right husband for you, and I don't know a lot

33:31.080 --> 33:31.900
about women.

33:32.920 --> 33:36.920
I can teach you about that, she said.

33:37.840 --> 33:41.660
He looked at her in surprise, and laughed.

33:42.500 --> 33:45.080
She was angry when he laughed.

33:46.280 --> 33:48.380
I'm nearly fifteen.

33:49.640 --> 33:53.960
In my village, a girl can have a husband when

33:53.960 --> 33:55.280
she is fifteen.

33:56.440 --> 33:58.580
Why are you laughing?

34:00.100 --> 34:02.920
I'm sorry, he said.

34:03.900 --> 34:11.160
You are a beautiful, interesting girl, Pocahontas, but you are

34:11.160 --> 34:12.540
only a child.

34:14.140 --> 34:16.300
I'm not a child.

34:17.260 --> 34:23.160
You're afraid of me, because I'm a king's daughter, and

34:23.160 --> 34:25.960
I want you for my husband.

34:28.200 --> 34:32.040
Pocahontas was angry and unhappy.

34:33.100 --> 34:38.280
She went away, back to her father's village, and she

34:38.280 --> 34:42.820
didn't visit John Smith again for two months.

34:43.920 --> 34:48.060
But she thought about him every day.

34:48.840 --> 34:53.920
There was only one man in the world for Pocahontas,

34:53.920 --> 34:57.140
and that was John Smith.

34:58.320 --> 35:05.700
And in Jamestown, perhaps John Smith thought about Pocahontas too.

35:24.840 --> 35:26.500
Chapter 5

35:27.500 --> 35:30.060
Where is John Smith?

35:31.760 --> 35:39.960
In the winter of 1608, the English in Jamestown were

35:39.960 --> 35:41.440
hungry again.

35:42.440 --> 35:51.140
So John Smith went to Werowakomoko and asked Powhatan for

35:51.140 --> 35:51.720
corn.

35:53.140 --> 35:59.120
He took many beautiful glass beads with him, because the

35:59.120 --> 36:01.840
Indians loved these things.

36:02.720 --> 36:07.060
But Powhatan wanted more than beads.

36:09.440 --> 36:16.460
You can have corn, he said, but you must build

36:16.460 --> 36:22.020
one of your big English houses for me, with windows

36:22.020 --> 36:23.240
of glass,

36:24.320 --> 36:28.260
and you must give me some guns.

36:29.720 --> 36:34.380
A house, yes, said Smith.

36:35.180 --> 36:42.640
Tomorrow my men can bring things from Jamestown and begin

36:42.640 --> 36:45.280
to build a house for you.

36:46.060 --> 36:46.960
But guns?

36:48.060 --> 36:48.580
No.

36:49.280 --> 36:52.060
Friends do not need guns.

36:54.680 --> 37:02.100
Powhatan smiled, but he was angry, very angry.

37:03.160 --> 37:07.900
Yes, we are friends, he said.

37:08.920 --> 37:13.360
Tonight you must stay here and eat with us.

37:14.240 --> 37:17.600
Tomorrow you can have your corn.

37:19.820 --> 37:25.680
That night Pocahontas came to John Smith.

37:26.740 --> 37:28.400
She was afraid.

37:29.580 --> 37:34.160
My father is angry, she said.

37:34.960 --> 37:39.420
He wants to kill you and all your men.

37:40.160 --> 37:42.340
You must be careful.

37:44.320 --> 37:47.720
John Smith took her hands.

37:48.760 --> 37:54.040
What a good friend you are, Pocahontas, he said.

37:55.120 --> 37:57.000
How can I thank you?

37:59.660 --> 38:03.240
Pocahontas looked into his blue eyes.

38:04.340 --> 38:08.520
You are my king, she said quietly.

38:08.520 --> 38:13.860
My king, now and always.

38:16.040 --> 38:22.160
So Smith and his men carried their guns all the

38:22.160 --> 38:25.740
time, and they watched very carefully.

38:26.980 --> 38:32.660
The next morning Opecan Canu and his women came with

38:32.660 --> 38:33.360
the corn.

38:35.980 --> 38:41.080
There is your corn, Opecan Canu said.

38:42.040 --> 38:46.400
Now, give us your guns, he smiled.

38:47.520 --> 38:49.120
Look behind you.

38:50.400 --> 38:57.160
Smith looked, and 700 Indians came out of the forest

38:57.160 --> 38:59.480
with bows and arrows.

39:00.480 --> 39:05.500
How can 10 men fight 700?

39:07.380 --> 39:13.620
In a second John Smith had his hand in Opecan

39:13.620 --> 39:19.440
Canu's hair and his gun in Opecan Canu's face.

39:21.980 --> 39:29.100
My gun can kill you, he said angrily, before an

39:29.100 --> 39:31.300
arrow can get to me.

39:32.780 --> 39:35.760
He looked at Opecan Canu's men.

39:37.160 --> 39:40.640
Do you want Opecan Canu to die?

39:41.700 --> 39:42.100
He called.

39:42.780 --> 39:47.440
The Indians were afraid of John Smith.

39:48.400 --> 39:52.660
To them he was a king, and it is not

39:52.660 --> 39:54.640
easy to kill a king.

39:55.740 --> 40:00.120
They put down their bows and arrows and went away

40:00.120 --> 40:01.520
into the forest.

40:02.980 --> 40:06.020
Opecan Canu too was afraid.

40:06.740 --> 40:11.500
His women put the corn in Smith's boat, and Smith

40:11.500 --> 40:16.000
and his men went back down the river to Jamestown.

40:18.620 --> 40:22.440
Powhatan and Opecan Canu were angry.

40:23.800 --> 40:28.620
We don't want these Englishmen in our country.

40:28.620 --> 40:33.700
Powhatan said, We must kill them.

40:34.140 --> 40:35.880
Kill them all.

40:37.040 --> 40:41.180
No father said Pocahontas.

40:41.860 --> 40:45.240
We must learn to be friends with the English.

40:46.180 --> 40:52.180
John Smith says, Be quiet, Powhatan said.

40:52.180 --> 40:55.700
John Smith is our enemy.

40:56.440 --> 40:58.020
Stay away from him.

40:58.740 --> 40:59.760
Do you understand?

41:02.060 --> 41:04.700
But you gave him to me, father.

41:05.640 --> 41:06.640
Do you remember?

41:07.920 --> 41:12.820
I loved his blue eyes then, and I love them

41:12.820 --> 41:13.380
now.

41:14.200 --> 41:16.880
I cannot stay away from him.

41:18.960 --> 41:24.800
Pocahontas did visit John Smith after that, but not very

41:24.800 --> 41:25.320
often.

41:26.080 --> 41:28.240
It wasn't easy for her.

41:29.040 --> 41:33.080
There was often fighting between the English and the Indians

41:33.080 --> 41:37.420
now, and dead men do not make friends.

41:38.820 --> 41:45.360
More ships and more men came from England and more

41:45.360 --> 41:45.860
guns.

41:47.120 --> 41:55.000
Jamestown was now a town of 500 people, 500 hungry

41:55.000 --> 41:55.840
people.

41:56.540 --> 42:03.040
The English wanted the Indians corn, and the Indians wanted

42:03.040 --> 42:04.880
the Englishmen's guns.

42:06.100 --> 42:14.880
One day, in October 1609, Pocahontas went to Jamestown, but

42:14.880 --> 42:17.400
she could not find John Smith.

42:18.860 --> 42:20.560
Where is he?

42:21.480 --> 42:23.360
She asked some Englishmen.

42:24.680 --> 42:25.680
Smith?

42:26.420 --> 42:29.240
He left Jamestown a month ago.

42:29.240 --> 42:31.240
One man said.

42:31.960 --> 42:35.400
He had a bad accident with some gunpowder.

42:36.520 --> 42:38.320
He was very ill.

42:39.100 --> 42:41.540
So he went home to England.

42:42.800 --> 42:43.800
Ill?

42:44.640 --> 42:45.780
Pocahontas said.

42:46.700 --> 42:48.380
John Smith is ill?

42:49.520 --> 42:52.120
Yes, the man said.

42:52.640 --> 42:58.560
It was a very bad accident, and six weeks on

42:58.560 --> 42:59.120
a ship.

42:59.920 --> 43:02.400
Perhaps he's dead now.

43:03.800 --> 43:07.760
Did he leave a letter for me?

43:08.740 --> 43:10.000
Pocahontas asked.

43:11.040 --> 43:12.760
The man laughed.

43:13.780 --> 43:19.100
A letter for you, little girl, but you can't read.

43:19.920 --> 43:20.580
Why?

43:20.580 --> 43:22.300
Is it important?

43:23.640 --> 43:26.120
No, she said.

43:26.740 --> 43:28.100
It's not important.

43:29.300 --> 43:31.940
But, of course, it was.

43:33.440 --> 43:38.660
She went away into the forest and cried for a

43:38.660 --> 43:39.900
long time.

43:40.920 --> 43:43.480
Where was John Smith?

43:44.140 --> 43:49.740
Her Englishman with blue eyes, the color of the sky.

44:08.560 --> 44:11.360
Chapter 6.

44:11.960 --> 44:14.840
A husband for Pocahontas.

44:16.280 --> 44:22.460
For four years after that, things were very bad.

44:23.540 --> 44:28.200
Sometimes Pocahontas tried to help the English.

44:29.220 --> 44:35.440
But to Powhatan and Opé Concanu, the English were enemies,

44:36.580 --> 44:39.240
and they wanted to kill them all.

44:41.040 --> 44:44.720
Powhatan gave the English no more corn.

44:46.000 --> 44:50.860
His men came at night to Jamestown and took guns

44:50.860 --> 44:52.280
and other things.

44:53.220 --> 44:58.080
When they found Englishmen in the forest or by the

44:58.080 --> 44:58.360
river,

44:59.200 --> 45:01.960
they killed them and took their guns.

45:02.660 --> 45:09.880
And so, Powhatan now had many guns in Whero Ocomical.

45:12.060 --> 45:17.940
The new leaders of Jamestown were very unhappy about this.

45:19.280 --> 45:23.500
How can we stop Powhatan, they said?

45:24.280 --> 45:27.820
We must get those guns back from him.

45:30.180 --> 45:35.200
We need to take a hostage, said a man called

45:35.200 --> 45:36.600
Samuel Argo.

45:37.480 --> 45:43.200
One of the chiefs, or somebody important from Powhatan's family,

45:44.380 --> 45:47.040
then we can talk to Powhatan.

45:47.460 --> 45:51.700
We can give him back the hostage when he gives

45:51.700 --> 45:52.640
us the guns,

45:53.240 --> 45:55.080
but not before.

45:58.260 --> 46:00.280
Powhatan has a daughter.

46:01.040 --> 46:03.920
Pocahontas, said an older man.

46:04.740 --> 46:07.900
He loves her very much, they say.

46:11.700 --> 46:16.340
In 1613, Pocahontas was 19.

46:17.860 --> 46:23.240
She lived now with her father's friend Ayapassus and his

46:23.240 --> 46:23.600
wife.

46:25.160 --> 46:30.260
Ayapassus was friendly with the English, and so it was

46:30.260 --> 46:32.680
easy for Samuel Argo.

46:33.480 --> 46:38.340
He came to Ayapassus' village in his ship.

46:40.140 --> 46:46.840
I have many beautiful things from England in my ship.

46:47.560 --> 46:52.620
He told Ayapassus, they are all for you.

46:53.400 --> 46:57.400
But first, you must give me something.

46:58.120 --> 47:04.340
You must bring Pocahontas onto my ship and leave her

47:04.340 --> 47:04.720
here.

47:06.400 --> 47:13.720
So Ayapassus took Pocahontas onto the ship and Argo locked

47:13.720 --> 47:14.860
her in a room.

47:16.380 --> 47:19.060
Pocahontas was very angry.

47:20.680 --> 47:26.740
I'm sorry, Argo said to her, but you must come

47:26.740 --> 47:28.740
with me to Jamestown.

47:29.460 --> 47:34.720
Your father must stop fighting us, and he must give

47:34.720 --> 47:36.180
us back our guns.

47:37.320 --> 47:39.780
Then you can go home.

47:41.560 --> 47:46.860
So Pocahontas went to Jamestown and stayed there.

47:47.640 --> 47:51.160
At first, Powhatan was angry.

47:52.040 --> 47:53.760
He wanted his daughter.

47:54.760 --> 47:59.680
But then he looked at his guns, and he wanted

47:59.680 --> 48:02.280
them more than his daughter.

48:04.740 --> 48:08.660
We can kill the English with these guns.

48:09.780 --> 48:14.920
He said to Opecan Canu, Pocahontas likes the English.

48:15.820 --> 48:20.700
She can stay in Jamestown and the guns can stay

48:20.700 --> 48:21.220
here.

48:24.300 --> 48:31.180
There were many women in Jamestown now, and Pocahontas soon

48:31.180 --> 48:32.980
made new friends.

48:34.020 --> 48:37.560
The English women liked her very much.

48:38.500 --> 48:43.900
She stayed in their houses, played with their children, and

48:43.900 --> 48:46.520
spoke English all the time.

48:47.520 --> 48:53.620
After some months, one of her new friends asked her,

48:54.380 --> 48:58.180
Are you happy here with us Pocahontas?

48:58.700 --> 49:02.040
Would you like to go home to your people?

49:03.020 --> 49:08.160
The English are my people now, said Pocahontas.

49:09.160 --> 49:14.480
But perhaps one day your father, said her friend.

49:16.020 --> 49:22.540
My father, said Pocahontas, likes his guns better than his

49:22.540 --> 49:23.000
daughter.

49:23.820 --> 49:26.380
They are more important to him.

49:27.160 --> 49:32.620
This is my home now, and I am very happy

49:32.620 --> 49:33.220
here.

49:34.620 --> 49:39.900
One of her new friends was a man called John

49:39.900 --> 49:40.340
Roth.

49:42.060 --> 49:43.600
Pocahontas liked him.

49:44.640 --> 49:48.580
Roth was a tall man with brown eyes.

49:49.500 --> 49:55.600
He liked Pocahontas too, and visited her nearly every day.

49:56.380 --> 50:01.060
He smiled a lot, and often laughed happily.

50:03.500 --> 50:11.860
One day, he said, Pocahontas, I have something important to

50:11.860 --> 50:12.640
say to you.

50:13.180 --> 50:20.360
We are good friends, I think, and, well, we can

50:20.360 --> 50:21.720
be more than friends.

50:22.720 --> 50:28.860
I need a wife, Pocahontas, and you are the most

50:28.860 --> 50:31.700
beautiful woman in Jamestown,

50:32.220 --> 50:35.520
and the most interesting woman too.

50:36.500 --> 50:42.000
I love you, Pocahontas, and I want to marry you.

50:43.520 --> 50:47.740
At first, Pocahontas didn't say anything.

50:48.580 --> 50:53.900
John Roth was a nice man, but a long time

50:53.900 --> 50:55.540
ago, she remembered,

50:56.340 --> 51:00.100
she wanted to be the wife of a different John.

51:01.600 --> 51:06.680
But I'm never going to see John Smith again, she

51:06.680 --> 51:07.080
thought.

51:07.860 --> 51:08.940
He's dead.

51:09.940 --> 51:11.900
I must forget about him.

51:14.260 --> 51:17.180
She smiled at John Roth.

51:18.040 --> 51:23.960
Yes, John, she said, I would very much like to

51:23.960 --> 51:25.260
be your wife.

51:27.580 --> 51:34.780
And so, on the 5th April, 1614, an Indian girl

51:34.780 --> 51:39.090
married an Englishman in the church in Jamestown.

51:41.410 --> 51:47.330
Pocahontas' father did not come, but Opecan Canu was there,

51:48.070 --> 51:49.630
with many of her people.

51:51.270 --> 51:54.310
Your father is happy for you.

51:55.170 --> 52:00.810
Opecan Canu told her, Pocahontas was happy too.

52:01.810 --> 52:06.330
John Roth was a good husband, and a year later,

52:07.030 --> 52:10.050
they had a little son, Thomas.

52:11.290 --> 52:14.310
Pocahontas loved him very much.

52:33.190 --> 52:35.030
Chapter 7

52:35.810 --> 52:36.530
England

52:38.790 --> 52:46.790
In 1616, Pocahontas, John Roth and their son went to

52:46.790 --> 52:47.250
England.

52:48.370 --> 52:51.030
Ten of her people came too.

52:51.870 --> 52:57.190
After seven weeks on the ship, they arrived in London.

52:58.190 --> 53:05.790
How big London is, Pocahontas said, there are hundreds of

53:05.790 --> 53:09.170
houses here and thousands of people.

53:10.310 --> 53:14.530
London was very noisy and exciting.

53:15.690 --> 53:19.410
Pocahontas was interested in everything.

53:20.410 --> 53:24.670
She went into the shops and looked at the food

53:24.670 --> 53:27.530
and the dresses and the books.

53:28.430 --> 53:32.630
She went up and down the river Thames in a

53:32.630 --> 53:37.010
boat and saw the big houses of rich people.

53:37.810 --> 53:43.170
Every day she saw something new and wonderful.

53:44.430 --> 53:50.710
But London was very dirty too, because there were so

53:50.710 --> 53:51.810
many people.

53:52.650 --> 53:56.570
The river was dirty and the water was bad.

53:57.510 --> 54:02.030
Two of Pocahontas's people were ill and died.

54:03.690 --> 54:08.370
But Pocahontas was happy and excited.

54:09.370 --> 54:14.850
Every day she visited big houses and talked to rich

54:14.850 --> 54:16.550
and important people.

54:17.470 --> 54:22.170
Everybody in London wanted to meet her, to talk to

54:22.170 --> 54:24.590
her, to be her friend.

54:26.410 --> 54:31.670
The king and queen of England heard about John Roth's

54:31.670 --> 54:34.870
wife, the Indian girl from Virginia,

54:35.670 --> 54:38.350
and they wanted to meet her too.

54:39.330 --> 54:45.270
So one day Pocahontas went to visit King James and

54:45.270 --> 54:46.270
Queen Anne.

54:47.230 --> 54:50.950
They asked her about her father, Powhatan.

54:51.770 --> 54:57.910
My father is the king of the Algonquin people, she

54:57.910 --> 54:58.310
said.

54:58.310 --> 55:05.590
He has many men and villages, but our country is

55:05.590 --> 55:07.210
quieter than England.

55:08.350 --> 55:13.870
Our people understand the forest and the animals and the

55:13.870 --> 55:14.150
rivers.

55:15.090 --> 55:19.610
You can learn from us and we can learn from

55:19.610 --> 55:20.290
you too.

55:21.110 --> 55:22.990
We must be friends.

55:24.550 --> 55:28.910
Of course we must, King James said.

55:29.730 --> 55:35.490
James Town has my name, so I'm very interested in

55:35.490 --> 55:35.670
it.

55:36.810 --> 55:42.690
They talked for some time, and then his wife, Queen

55:42.690 --> 55:44.410
Anne, said,

55:44.410 --> 55:49.030
I have a letter about you Pocahontas.

55:49.690 --> 55:53.150
It's from a man called John Smith.

55:54.070 --> 55:58.630
He was your friend, he says, when you were a

55:58.630 --> 55:59.290
little girl.

56:00.050 --> 56:01.370
Is that true?

56:03.370 --> 56:08.790
For a second or two Pocahontas could not speak.

56:09.790 --> 56:17.030
Then she said, a letter from John Smith, but he's

56:17.030 --> 56:17.470
dead.

56:18.530 --> 56:20.850
Queen Anne smiled.

56:21.930 --> 56:22.730
Dead?

56:23.630 --> 56:26.510
No, he's here in England.

56:27.370 --> 56:30.050
Look, here is the letter.

56:31.210 --> 56:33.930
The queen looked at Pocahontas.

56:35.350 --> 56:37.770
What's the matter, my dear?

56:38.550 --> 56:39.630
Are you ill?

56:40.830 --> 56:44.990
No, no, I'm all right.

56:46.010 --> 56:47.210
I'm very happy.

56:48.470 --> 56:53.650
But that night Pocahontas could not sleep.

56:54.530 --> 56:56.650
She was very excited.

56:57.470 --> 57:00.490
John Smith was not dead.

57:01.110 --> 57:06.610
He was alive, and in England, but where?

57:08.230 --> 57:13.690
Two days later John Smith came to see her.

57:14.690 --> 57:19.430
He was older, of course, but she remembered him.

57:20.190 --> 57:27.330
A little man, not tall, but interesting, exciting, alive.

57:28.330 --> 57:33.210
He smiled at her with those beautiful blue eyes.

57:34.410 --> 57:37.490
Hello, Pocahontas, he said.

57:38.570 --> 57:40.010
Do you remember me?

57:41.270 --> 57:43.710
How could she forget him?

57:44.610 --> 57:47.910
She looked at him, but said nothing.

57:49.110 --> 57:51.190
John Rolf watched them.

57:52.570 --> 57:56.830
It's John Smith, my dear, he said.

57:57.730 --> 57:59.910
Are you happy to see him?

58:01.190 --> 58:04.910
But Pocahontas was not happy.

58:06.050 --> 58:08.490
No, she said.

58:09.250 --> 58:10.390
I'm sorry.

58:11.270 --> 58:11.770
No.

58:12.750 --> 58:16.650
She looked out of the window at nothing.

58:17.620 --> 58:20.530
She couldn't look at John Smith.

58:22.450 --> 58:26.790
John Rolf went out, and Smith waited.

58:27.930 --> 58:30.610
After a minute, he said,

58:31.490 --> 58:35.650
You are a wife now, and a mother.

58:38.330 --> 58:43.390
Yes, Pocahontas looked at him and tried to smile.

58:44.390 --> 58:47.070
Do I look different?

58:47.810 --> 58:48.450
He asked.

58:49.490 --> 58:51.190
I'm older, I know.

58:51.990 --> 58:53.050
No.

58:53.870 --> 58:57.470
You don't look different, she said.

58:58.230 --> 59:02.950
But why did you go away from Virginia?

59:05.010 --> 59:08.590
I had an accident, he said.

59:09.590 --> 59:11.330
I was very ill.

59:12.170 --> 59:17.430
So I came back to England, and after two years,

59:18.090 --> 59:18.810
I got better.

59:21.230 --> 59:24.850
In Jamestown, they told me you were dead.

59:26.230 --> 59:26.670
Dead?

59:27.410 --> 59:29.070
No, not me.

59:30.210 --> 59:32.610
But you didn't tell me.

59:33.170 --> 59:35.410
You didn't write me a letter.

59:36.140 --> 59:40.410
Not one letter in eight years, John Smith.

59:42.060 --> 59:44.990
But you were a child, Pocahontas.

59:45.430 --> 59:46.750
You couldn't read.

59:47.910 --> 59:53.450
Well, I can read now, she said, angrily.

59:54.550 --> 59:58.430
Perhaps I was a child, John Smith.

59:59.090 --> 01:00:02.110
But my father gave you to me.

01:00:02.650 --> 01:00:06.670
That day in my father's village, long ago,

01:00:07.650 --> 01:00:08.890
do you remember?

01:00:09.730 --> 01:00:14.390
That day was the beginning of my love for you.

01:00:17.730 --> 01:00:23.210
He looked at her sadly with those beautiful blue eyes,

01:00:24.050 --> 01:00:26.070
and she was a child again.

01:00:26.810 --> 01:00:29.430
She remembered everything.

01:00:31.110 --> 01:00:34.950
You didn't love me, she said.

01:00:35.550 --> 01:00:37.950
You never loved me.

01:00:41.630 --> 01:00:47.230
I don't know about love, he said slowly.

01:00:48.470 --> 01:00:52.970
You are the daughter of a king, Pocahontas,

01:00:53.450 --> 01:00:57.510
and I'm not rich or important.

01:00:58.510 --> 01:01:00.590
I never had a wife.

01:01:01.670 --> 01:01:04.930
Perhaps I don't understand women.

01:01:05.690 --> 01:01:09.030
And you were a child, Pocahontas.

01:01:10.390 --> 01:01:15.070
I was a child, but I loved you,

01:01:15.830 --> 01:01:19.150
and you went away, she said.

01:01:19.930 --> 01:01:24.750
For eight years, I heard nothing from you.

01:01:26.450 --> 01:01:30.510
For a long time, he said nothing.

01:01:31.510 --> 01:01:36.790
Then he said, I'm sorry, Pocahontas.

01:01:37.630 --> 01:01:39.130
I was wrong.

01:01:40.930 --> 01:01:46.610
I loved you so much, she said sadly.

01:01:47.590 --> 01:01:52.930
Then the door opened, and her little son, Thomas, came

01:01:52.930 --> 01:01:53.290
in.

01:01:54.590 --> 01:02:00.190
But now I have a son and a husband, she

01:02:00.190 --> 01:02:00.570
said,

01:02:01.610 --> 01:02:03.110
and they love me.

01:02:04.130 --> 01:02:07.270
You and I cannot be friends.

01:02:08.490 --> 01:02:10.870
Goodbye, John Smith.

01:02:12.770 --> 01:02:14.830
Goodbye, Pocahontas.

01:02:16.590 --> 01:02:19.270
He looked at her for a minute,

01:02:19.270 --> 01:02:22.350
and then walked out of the door.

01:02:23.530 --> 01:02:25.530
She never saw him again.

01:02:27.170 --> 01:02:31.350
Six months later, John Rolf said,

01:02:32.150 --> 01:02:35.410
We must go back to Virginia, my dear.

01:02:36.230 --> 01:02:38.710
My work is waiting for me there,

01:02:39.530 --> 01:02:43.450
and you need the warm son of Virginia too.

01:02:44.330 --> 01:02:45.990
It was true.

01:02:47.290 --> 01:02:49.590
Pocahontas was now ill,

01:02:50.230 --> 01:02:54.710
and the cold rain of the English winter was not

01:02:54.710 --> 01:02:55.730
good for her.

01:02:56.850 --> 01:03:01.150
But she said nothing and got ready to leave.

01:03:02.350 --> 01:03:05.770
The ship went down the river from London

01:03:05.770 --> 01:03:10.550
to a town called Graves End near the sea.

01:03:11.250 --> 01:03:13.610
But when they got there,

01:03:13.610 --> 01:03:16.710
Pocahontas was very ill,

01:03:17.450 --> 01:03:19.010
and she could not move.

01:03:20.330 --> 01:03:23.910
John Rolf sat by his wife's bed

01:03:23.910 --> 01:03:27.290
and watched her face sadly.

01:03:28.990 --> 01:03:31.330
She smiled at him.

01:03:32.610 --> 01:03:34.210
Goodbye, John.

01:03:35.410 --> 01:03:36.950
I am going home.

01:03:38.050 --> 01:03:42.410
Home to the forests and rivers of my country.

01:03:46.550 --> 01:03:52.470
Pocahontas died in Graves End in March 1617.

01:03:53.790 --> 01:03:57.050
She is famous for two things.

01:03:58.390 --> 01:04:00.550
She was the first American woman

01:04:00.550 --> 01:04:04.390
to marry an English man and come to England.

01:04:05.630 --> 01:04:08.830
And she was a good friend to the English

01:04:08.830 --> 01:04:11.310
when they first went to Virginia.

01:04:13.610 --> 01:04:15.810
Her husband, John Rolf,

01:04:16.250 --> 01:04:20.790
went back to Virginia and married an English woman there.

01:04:21.630 --> 01:04:25.850
He died in Virginia in 1622.

01:04:27.290 --> 01:04:29.670
Pocahontas' son, Thomas,

01:04:30.390 --> 01:04:34.170
lived with the Rolf family in England when he was

01:04:34.170 --> 01:04:34.750
a child,

01:04:34.750 --> 01:04:40.530
but in 1635 he went to live in Virginia.

01:04:42.410 --> 01:04:46.430
John Smith did not leave England again.

01:04:47.310 --> 01:04:51.030
He wrote many interesting books about America,

01:04:51.890 --> 01:04:55.450
and he wrote about Pocahontas in those books.

01:04:56.290 --> 01:05:02.450
He lived until 1631, but he never had a wife.

01:05:02.450 --> 01:05:08.990
Perhaps he could not forget the sad, dark eyes of

01:05:08.990 --> 01:05:10.010
Pocahontas

01:05:10.010 --> 01:05:14.950
when she said goodbye to him for the last time.

